                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 774/79–81.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        Ambassador <persName type="to">White</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,<date calendar="gregorian" when="1907-06-19">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 19, 1907</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>(Mr. Root informs Mr. White that the Governments of Germany, Great Britain,
                    Holland, and Japan are prepared to join the United States in appointing
                    commissioners jointly to investigate the opium question provided that the
                    cooperation of China is assured and provided that the inquiry covers the
                    production of opium in China as well as its importation. States that the Chinese
                    Government is favorably disposed and will doubtless appoint a commissioner, and
                    adds that before proceeding further the reply of France is necessary. Directs
                    Mr. White to see instruction No. 254 of January 31.)</p>
            </div>
        </body>
